</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/uvizco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>vizco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/1/02 10:26:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.harmonyofsouls.org/pics/hosicon_flag.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The war of northern agression</span><hr size=1> If there had been no slavery, do you seriously think the Civil War would have happened?<br>
<br>
Nope.<br>
<br>
The South seceded to protect its right to enslave other humans. Lincoln's party had a big component of abolitionists in it and the South feared he would try to restrict or abolish slavery, in spite of his denials.<br>
<br>
The North fought initially to preserve the union, and tried terribly hard to ignore slavery as an issue, because they wanted to keep Maryland, Delaware and Kentucky in the union, and those were slave-holding states.<br>
<br>
As the war went on, as so often happens, the war aims of the North expanded from preservation of the union to abolition of slavery. A reason of pure politics (since you don't want to admit anyone could be so altruistic as to want to free someone from bondage) was to dissuade (on moral grounds) Britain and France from intervening on behalf of the South.<br>
<br>
But to say that no one in the North cared about slavery is so completely, utterly, wrongheaded that I can't help but /boggle.<br>
<br>
People in the North had horribly racist attitudes about black people, but they were not fans of slavery either.<br>
<br>
My town is full of stops on the Underground Railroad. People rioted in Boston to prevent captured slaves from being returned to their masters in the South.<br>
<br>
&quot;Uncle Tom's Cabin&quot; was not a best seller because it attacked states' rights, but because it graphically exposed the evils of slavery.<br>
<br>
